Shortest Path in Binary Matrix 
This repository contains a Python implementation of the Shortest Path in a Binary Matrix problem using Breadth-First Search (BFS).
The goal is to find the shortest path from the top-left corner of the grid to the bottom-right corner, moving through cells with value 0, and movement is allowed in eight directions.

Problem Description

You are given an n x n binary matrix grid where:

0 means the cell is open

1 means the cell is blocked

Your task is to return the length of the shortest clear path, starting at (0,0) and ending at (n-1,n-1).

A clear path means:

Every visited cell must be 0

Movement is allowed in 8 directions: up, down, left, right, and all diagonals

If no valid path exists, return -1.

ğŸ¯ Why BFS?

This problem is a classic case of shortest path in an unweighted grid.
Breadth-First Search guarantees the shortest path because:

It explores level by level

The first time you reach the destination, that path is the shortest

BFS avoids unnecessary paths

This makes BFS the ideal solution.

ğŸ”„ Movement Directions

These 8 directions are used:

